        <page n="02" image="pa.fr.vs.1861.10.23.02">
            <div type="a">
                <column>1</column>
                <head>A Literary Boomerang</head>
                <origin>Boston Courier</origin>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>A critique of Charles Sumner.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>4</column>
                <head>Archbishop Hughes on Slavery and the War</head>
                <origin>Metropolitan Review</origin>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>An article from Rev. Hughes criticizing the abolitionist war aims of a
                    Catholic who published an article in Brownson's Review. Rev. Hughes asserts that
                    a push for equal rights for blacks will result in a backlash that will leave
                    blacks in a worse state.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <pageNote/>
        </page>
        <page n="03" image="pa.fr.vs.1861.10.23.03">
            <div type="a">
                <column>1</column>
                <head>Good Signs</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Happily reports that the leading Republican newspapers in Massachusetts are
                    critical of Sumner's abolition speech made to the Republican State Convention.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <pageNote>Column 1 is a continuation of Hughes' article. Remainder of page
                advertisements.</pageNote>
        </page>
